{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18064"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18064"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.09,0.18,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76758"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10778"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62251"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5672"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76758"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is observing in the emergency department. Before examining a patient with abdominal pain, the supervising doctor asks for and receives verbal permission from the patient for the student to participate in the examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate way to document this verbal consent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No documentation is required","Patient happy for student to examine","Student examination approved verbally","Verbal consent obtained from patient today","Patient verbally agreed to student involvement"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct documentation should state \u003Cstrong\u003EPatient verbally agreed to student involvement\u003C/strong\u003E. This clearly indicates the specific nature of what was agreed to and uses professional language appropriate for medical records.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are problematic because:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo documentation required for verbal consent\u003C/strong\u003E - All forms of consent, whether verbal or written, must be documented in the medical record to maintain an accurate record of patient interactions.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient happy for student to examine\u003C/strong\u003E - This uses colloquial language that is inappropriate for medical documentation and lacks professional terminology.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudent examination approved verbally\u003C/strong\u003E - This uses passive voice which fails to clearly identify who provided the consent, making the documentation ambiguous.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerbal consent obtained from patient today\u003C/strong\u003E - This statement is too vague as it does not specify what the consent was for, which could lead to confusion or misinterpretation.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EDocumentation of verbal consent should be clear, specific, and professional. While written consent is required for more significant procedures, verbal consent is appropriate for low-risk activities like student participation in examination, provided it is properly documented.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Verbal consent must be documented in the medical record with date, time, and name of person providing consent.","Verbal consent is only appropriate for low-risk procedures where written consent is impractical.","The person providing verbal consent must have capacity and be given adequate information about risks and benefits."],"references":["Informed consent in health care. Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care. 2020. Available from: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/2020-09/sq20-030_-_fact_sheet_-_informed_consent_-_nsqhs-8.9a.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18064"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62251"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T08:07:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T08:08:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10778"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76758"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)",